data.content:
Your assertions work but produce unhelpful failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest has dedicated APIs for collections:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Count — clear failure message with expected vs actual
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // All items match a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"),
        "Expected an Admin user in results");
}
```

**Key MSTest collection tools:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(item != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(item)` | Clearer failure message |

**`CollectionAssert`** for richer checks:

```csharp
// All elements satisfy a type
CollectionAssert.AllAreSameType(users);

// Exact elements (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Same elements, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Membership
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
```

**Rule of thumb:** avoid `Assert.IsTrue(bool)` — it tells you *nothing* on failure. Use the most specific assert available so failures show *what* went wrong (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 1").
